{{EngvarB|date=June 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}} {{Infobox national netball team | country = Malawi | image = | imagesize = | caption = | nickname = Queens | association = Netball Association of Malawi | confederation = Africa Netball | coach = Whyte Mlilima (caretaker) | asst coach = Griffin Saenda Jr | manager = | captain = | vice-captain = | caps = | top scorer = | rank = 6 <!--Uniforms colours--> | kitlabel1 = | body1 = maroon | pattern_b1 = | skirt1 = maroon | pattern_sk1 = | kitlabel2 = | body2 = maroon | pattern_b2 = | skirt2 = black | pattern_sk2 = <!--Internationals--> | first game = | largest win = | largest loss = | WNC apps = | WNC debut = | WNC recent = 6th | WNC best = 5th ([[2007 World Netball Championships|2007]]) | CWG apps = | CWG debut = | CWG prev = 2018 | CWG recent = 7th | CWG best = 5th ([[Netball at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|2010]]), ([[Netball at the 2014 Commonwealth Games|2014]]) }} The '''Malawi national netball team''', nicknamed "The Queens", represent [[Malawi]] in international [[netball]] competition.
==History== Malawi have played in five [[World Netball Championships]], famously finishing fifth in [[2007 World Netball Championships|2007]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Gay |first=Edward |date=17 November 2007 |title=Jubilant Malawi finish fifth |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10476685 |newspaper=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> The Queens are coached by Whyte Mlilima, who was appointed as caretaker head coach after former coach Griffin Saenda had to withdraw from the team with medical problems.<ref name=Mbewe/> As of January 2018, the team are sixth in the [[INF World Rankings]].
In 2012 they competed in the [[2012 Fast5 Netball World Series|Fast5]] tournament in [[Auckland]], where they have had several historic results including wins over [[Australian national netball team|Australia]] and [[England national netball team|England]], and finished in 5th place, just narrowly missing out on the finals. This followed a draw against Australia in the [[2010 World Netball Series|2010 Edition]]. Airtel Malawi is a significant financial donor of the Malawi Queens, having sponsored their trip to Auckland for the Fast5 World Series in 2014 to a sum of K6 M.<ref>[http://www.faceofmalawi.com/2014/10/airtel-mw-sponsors-malawi-queens-with-k6-m/ Face of Malawi, Oct 29, 2014]</ref> The current Netball Association of Malawi (NAM) president is Carol Bapu.
At the [[Netball at the 2018 Commonwealth Games|2018 Commonwealth Games]], Malawi defeated the second-ranked team in the world, [[New Zealand national netball team|New Zealand]], for the first time in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/commonwealth-games/minnows-malawi-shock-silver-ferns-to-leave-new-zealand-in-danger-of-missing-commonwealth-games-glory/news-story/6bcc0c8ef317b46f2af0048b080f7d47|title=Minnows Malawi shock Silver Ferns to leave New Zealand in danger of missing Commonwealth Games glory|work=News.com.au|date=8 April 2018}}</ref>
